lg|c|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   In high level competitive auctions it is sometimes difficult to tell whether the hand belongs  to YOU or OPPS and, more importantly, it is often very difficult to tell whether to bid one more, double for penalties or pass.

^*bNon-Penalty Slam Doubles ^*n and ^*b Control-denying Doubles ^*n 
|n^|9|at| 
help you and your partner to make the right decision in these sorts of situations, but they are used in slightly different kinds of situation.

Non-Penalty slam doubles are used when you think it is THEIR hand, and we are thinking of sacrificing over their contract.

Control-denying (AKA control-showing) doubles are used when we think it is OUR hand and they have already sacrificed over OUR contract.

These kinds of doubles are NOT about getting a penalty, but to help you and your partner decide whether to bid one more or not.

Normally it is fairly easy to tell to whom the hand really belongs and whether you (or they) are bidding to make or sacrificing, but sometimes it can be a very difficult question to judge and it's not necessarily a matter of which side has more high cards.

Both of these kinds of double are used   ^*b only at the 5-level or higher^*n.

We'll look at Control-denying doubles first, because they are arguably easier to understand.|
