cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   Control-denying doubles are used in the following situation ONLY:- 
|n^|5|at|
^c ^*b1. ^*n  They have sacrificed over our game or slam contract.
|n^|5|at|
^c ^*b2. ^*n        2nd-in-hand over their sacrifice is NOT the Captain of the Hand 
              ^*bor^*n   there is no Captain of the hand at this stage.
|n^|5|at|
^c ^*b3. ^*n  Control of THEIR suit has ^*bNOT ^*n yet been firmly established by Asking bids (ie: Epsilon) or by cue-bids.
|n^|5|at|
^c ^*b4. ^*n  The question at hand is whether we 
^d           double their sacrifice for penalties 
^d  OR    bid one more
|n^|c|at|
^c     and     this mainly hinges on whether or not we have 1st (or 2nd) round Control of ^*b their ^*n suit
|n^|2|at|
As regards (4) above, if we're thinking of bidding one more at the ^*b 6-level^*n, 
	^c then we're normally concerned with whether we have ^*b 1st  or  2nd ^*n round control of their suit.
|n^|a|at|
but if we're thinking of bidding one more at the  ^*b7-level^*n, 
^c then we're definitely thinking of ^*b 1st round ^*n control in their suit.
