cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   Non-Penalty Slam Doubles (NSDP's) are a bit more complicated than Control-denying doubles, but the underlying principle is surprisingly similar.

Non-Penalty Slam Doubles  mainly apply at the 6-level.  When it's THEIR hand but we've already established earlier in the bidding that we do have a potential sacrifice (ie: by bidding and strongly supporting a suit ourselves)

then, when considering whether or not to sacrifice over their contract,  the following applies: 

^b  ^*b2nd-in-Hand^*n 
^d   PASSES  ^g with  1 or more  defensive tricks.
^c   or
^d   DOUBLES ^g with  NO  defensive tricks.

...that is the easy bit (as with Control-showing doubles, the ^*b pass ^*n is effectively ^*b stronger ^*n than the double).  


If  2nd-in-Hand  PASSES  then

^c ^*b4th-in-Hand^*n     
^e  PASSES with  1 or more  defensive tricks  (because we think they can't make their contract 
^s if we have 2 defensive tricks).
^d  or 
^e  DOUBLES with  NO  defensive tricks  (Now 2nd-in-hand sacrifices if they have only 1 defensive trick
^s but passes with 2 or more tricks).

(That's why NPSD's mainly apply at the 6-level.  All the maths has to be done differently if we're at the 5 or 7-level).|
