cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|     Note - @2it doesn't matter whether we're considering sacrificing at the 6-level in a higher-ranking suit or at the 7-level in a lower-ranking suit, if we're considering whether to sacrifice or not, one of the main things to decide is whether we can beat  THEIR  6-level contract.    
^b@2
If  2nd-in-Hand  DOUBLED  then

^c ^*b4th-in-Hand^*n     
^e   PASSES        with  2 or more  defensive tricks.
^d   or
^e   SACRIFICES with  NO or only 1  defensive trick.

|n^|9|at|
So if  2nd-in-hand  doubles to show  NO  defensive tricks and you have 2 defensive tricks, you pass, 
^t but otherwise you sacrifice.

But if  @22nd-in-hand  passes to show  1 or more  defensive tricks and you have  1 or more  defensive tricks then you also pass, but you double if you have no defensive tricks so partner (2nd-in-hand) can now pass or sacrifice depending on whether she has TWO defensive tricks rather than only 1.

^b@2Note:   This sort of sequence is NOT about taking a big penalty from Opps The whole idea behind Non-Penalty Slam Doubles is NOT to get a large penalty, but to avoid a costly sacrifice when the probability is that Opps are too high themselves.

If it's  THEIR  hand then even a small penalty is good enough for us to get a decent result.|
