cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|    Let's have a very brief look at Lead-directing doubles.
|n^|3|at|
These need to be used with care, as indiscriminate use of them can give needless information away to your opponents and can sometimes be counter-productive.
|n^|3|at|
Firstly, making a lead-directing double when it's probable that YOU are going to be on the opening lead is pretty much a waste of time and can only tip off Declarer to the lie of that particular suit, or the fact that it's breaking badly or that they may have an unexpectedly high number of quick losers in the suit.
|n^|3|at|
I concede that sometimes you cannot tell who is going to be Declarer at the point where you get the opportunity to make your lead-directing double, but very often you do have a fairly good idea.
|n^|3|at|
Remember that you do not always have to double the suit itself to ask for a lead of the suit.
|n^|3|at|
For example: Opps bid 
|n^|9|at|
^c (1@d) - (1@s)       (1NT) - (2NT)      (3NT) - (pass) - ???
|n^|9|at|
This is a good time for a Double if you are sat with a good Spade tenace over your RHO  (eg: @sAQ109x).   Opps are potentially stretching to get to 3NT and an initial Spade lead from Partner will give you a tempo, at the very least.
|n^|3|at|
Without your double it's much less likely that they'll hit on a @s lead. 
|n^|3|at|
But a Double here from a hand that's not bid anything to date is clearly asking partner for a lead of DUMMY's suit especially since they've only mentioned it once and their partner, Declarer, clearly doesn't have much support for it.

On the other hand, with a holding such as  @sK98xx,  I'd probably not bother, as you cannot be sure that a Spade lead will even help you.|
